## Security Review — `app.js`

**Overall Risk: Medium** (for what's here) → **High** (as a pattern to build on without remediation)

The file is a minimal Express.js application. While it has no obviously exploitable code *today*, it has numerous missing security controls that make it unsafe to expand upon or deploy as-is.

---

### 🔴 HIGH — Missing Authentication & Authorization

**`GET /users` is completely unauthenticated.** It exposes PII (names + email addresses) to any caller with no credential check.

```js
// ❌ Current — anyone can enumerate all users
app.get('/users', (req, res) => {
  res.json([{ id: 1, name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' }, ...]);
});

// ✅ Fix — add authentication middleware
const authenticate = (req, res, next) => {
  const token = req.headers['authorization']?.split(' ')[1];
  if (!token) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Unauthorized' });

  try {
    req.user = jwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_SECRET);
    next();
  } catch {
    return res.status(403).json({ error: 'Forbidden' });
  }
};

app.get('/users', authenticate, (req, res) => { ... });
```

---

### 🔴 HIGH — No Security Headers (OWASP A05: Security Misconfiguration)

Express by default sends an `X-Powered-By: Express` header (fingerprinting) and sets **no** protective headers (no CSP, no HSTS, no `X-Frame-Options`, etc.).

```js
// ✅ Fix — add helmet at the very top, before any routes
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet()); // Disables X-Powered-By, sets 11+ security headers at once
```

Install with: `npm install helmet`

---

### 🔴 HIGH — No Rate Limiting (OWASP A07: Identification & Auth Failures / DoS)

There is no rate limiting on any endpoint. This allows brute-force, credential stuffing, and denial-of-service attacks.

```js
// ✅ Fix
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

const limiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, // 15 minutes
  max: 100,                  // limit each IP to 100 requests per window
  standardHeaders: true,
  legacyHeaders: false,
});

app.use(limiter); // apply globally, or scope to sensitive routes
```

Install with: `npm install express-rate-limit`

---

### 🟠 MEDIUM — No CORS Policy (OWASP A01: Broken Access Control)

Without explicit CORS configuration, behavior depends on the browser and whether other middleware is added. Any web page can make credentialed cross-origin requests to this API.

```js
// ✅ Fix — restrict to known origins
const cors = require('cors');

app.use(cors({
  origin: ['https://yourdomain.com'],  // explicit allowlist — NOT '*' for authenticated APIs
  methods: ['GET', 'POST'],
  allowedHeaders: ['Authorization', 'Content-Type'],
}));
```

---

### 🟠 MEDIUM — Information Disclosure via `/health` (OWASP A05)

The health endpoint returns `timestamp: new Date().toISOString()`. In isolation this seems benign, but when health endpoints also leak version info, env names, or dependency versions (a common pattern), they become a reconnaissance target.

```js
// ❌ Current
res.json({ status: 'ok', timestamp: new Date().toISOString() });

// ✅ Fix — keep health responses minimal; never expose internals
app.get('/health', (req, res) => {
  res.json({ status: 'ok' });
});
```

---

### 🟠 MEDIUM — No Body Parsing / Input Validation Middleware (OWASP A03: Injection)

There is no `express.json()` or input validation middleware registered. The moment someone adds a `POST` route that reads `req.body`, it will be `undefined` unless the parser is present — leading to silent data handling bugs or prototype-pollution vectors if an unsafe parser is added ad-hoc later.

```js
// ✅ Fix — register parsers with size limits now, before any routes
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));       // prevents payload bombing
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: false, limit: '10kb' }));

// For any route accepting user input, use a validation library:
const { body, validationResult } = require('express-validator');

app.post('/users', authenticate, [
  body('email').isEmail().normalizeEmail(),
  body('name').isString().trim().isLength({ min: 1, max: 100 }).escape(),
], (req, res) => {
  const errors = validationResult(req);
  if (!errors.isEmpty()) return res.status(400).json({ errors: errors.array() });
  // ... safe to proceed
});
```

---

### 🟠 MEDIUM — No Global Error Handler (Information Leakage)

Unhandled errors in Express default to sending stack traces in the response body, leaking file paths, dependency versions, and internal logic.

```js
// ✅ Fix — add a catch-all error handler as the LAST middleware
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err); // log internally (use a structured logger like pino/winston)
  res.status(err.status || 500).json({ error: 'An unexpected error occurred' });
  // Never send err.message or err.stack to clients in production
});
```

---

